      <language langcode="eng" scriptcode="Latn">English</language>
    </langmaterial>
  </did>
  <scopecontent id="aspace_314af13197bb93edad7daba7c8af9f67">
    <head>Scope and Contents</head>
<p>The Dr. Joseph Pfeifer papers, circa 1900-2013, include materials related to the personal life and political and medical careers of Dr. Joseph L. Pfeifer. The files from his medical career mostly cover his time as a student at the Long Island College Hospital, and early career at St. Catharine's Hospital. Certificates and honors from regional medical societies are also a part of these papers. </p><p>The bulk of this collection is made up of materials from his time in the United States House of Representatives from 1935-1951. His service on the House Subcommittee of Foreign Affairs during and post-World War II is well-represented in memos, itineraries, and photographs. Ephemera from his 1930s election and re-election campaigns is also well-represented. </p><p>The Pfeifer and McKean Family papers make up a smaller part of the collection with newspaper clippings, ephemera related to institutions Joseph Pfeifer was related to through his children or siblings, and photographs from the Pfeifer Family and Adeline McKean, Dr. Pfeifer's wife.</p>  </scopecontent>
  <arrangement id="aspace_5c6c5b1d46220e33447c44be931f9982">
    <head>Arrangement</head>
<p>This collection is organized into three series:</p><p>- Series 1: Pfeifer and McKean family papers, circa 1900-2013</p><p>- Series 2: Physician files, 1910-1974 </p><p>- Series 3: U.S. House of Representatives files, 1919-1950</p>  </arrangement>
  <bioghist id="aspace_07d89413aa18e2b6df01adffa392d962">
    <head>Biographical Note</head>
<p>Joseph L. Pfeifer was born on February 6, 1892 in Brooklyn, New York to Henry Pfeifer and Mary Gabriel, immigrants from Reifenberg, Germany. The Pfeifers had 14 children. Joseph Pfeifer attended St. Leonard's Academy and St. Francis College in Brooklyn. He graduated from Long Island Medical College in 1914 and began his internship at St. Catharine's Hospital in Bushwick. Pfeifer married Adeline McKean, a graduate from St. Catharine's nursing school, in 1917. </p><p>The Pfeifers first lived at 33 Orient Avenue and had their first child in 1917. They later moved to 58 Bushwick Avenue, which had a basement office from which Dr. Pfeifer could practice medicine. They had 7 children: Frances, Loretta, Adeline, Joseph, Jr., Thomas, Monica, and Anne. They owned a second home in Forestburgh, NY, which they bought in 1930.</p><p>During World War I, Pfeifer was appointed to a medical advisory board instructing medical officers going overseas. After the war, he returned to St. Catharine's Hospital as a surgeon, eventually becoming Chief of Surgery there. He became a Fellow of the American College of Surgeons in Philadelphia in 1925 and was an Instructor in Surgery at Long Island College Hospital starting in 1927.</p><p>Dr. Pfeifer ran for Congress in 1934 in the 3rd district of New York City. He respresented the district until 1945. In 1944, he was elected representative for the 8th District and served as representative for that district until 1951. He was chosen for the House Foreign Affairs Committee during his first term and toured recovering areas post-World War II. During his time in Congress, he continued to perform surgeries at St. Catharine's Hospital. Dr. Pfeifer supported legislation that benefitted his Italian and Italian-American constituency, post-war reconstruction of Italy, and environmental protection. </p><p>Dr. Pfeifer retired from the attending staff of St. Catharine's in 1957 when he reached retirement age. He stopped practicing medicine in 1967 because of health complications. Dr. Pfeifer died on April 19, 1974 and was buried in St. John's Cemetery in Queens.</p>  </bioghist>
